{"award_age":47.0,"bio_image":"full\/343d5f0a45e05291307a85f63a1c01f3f708ef46.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1931-08-23T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/c\/c0\/Hamilton_Smith%2C_2.jpg\/220px-Hamilton_Smith%2C_2.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith","mini_bio":"<p><b>Hamilton Othanel Smith<\/b> (born August 23, 1931) is an American <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Microbiologist\" title=\"Microbiologist\">microbiologist<\/a> and Nobel laureate.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gitschier_2012_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-Gitschier_2012-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Smith was born on August 23, 1931, and graduated from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_Laboratory_High_School_of_Urbana,_Illinois\" title=\"University Laboratory High School of Urbana, Illinois\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University Laboratory High School of Urbana, Illinois<\/a>. He attended the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Illinois_at_Urbana-Champaign\" title=\"University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign<\/a>, but in 1950 transferred to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_California,_Berkeley\" title=\"University of California, Berkeley\">University of California, Berkeley<\/a>, where he earned his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bachelor_of_Arts\" title=\"Bachelor of Arts\">B.A.<\/a> in Mathematics in 1952 <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http:\/\/cal.berkeley.edu\">[1]<\/a>. He received his medical degree from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Johns_Hopkins_University\" title=\"Johns Hopkins University\">Johns Hopkins University<\/a> in 1956. In 1975, he was awarded a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Guggenheim_Fellowship\" title=\"Guggenheim Fellowship\">Guggenheim Fellowship<\/a> he spent at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Zurich\" title=\"University of Zurich\">University of Zurich<\/a>.<\/p><p>In 1970, Smith and Kent W. Wilcox discovered the first type II <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Restriction_enzyme\" title=\"Restriction enzyme\">restriction enzyme<\/a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> that is now called as <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/HindII\" title=\"HindII\">HindII<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gitschier_2012_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-Gitschier_2012-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Smith went on to discover DNA <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Methylase\" title=\"Methylase\" class=\"mw-redirect\">methylases<\/a> that constitute the other half of the bacterial host restriction and modification systems, as hypothesized by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Werner_Arber\" title=\"Werner Arber\">Werner Arber<\/a> of Switzerland.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gitschier_2012_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-Gitschier_2012-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>He was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1978 for discovering type II <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Restriction_enzyme\" title=\"Restriction enzyme\">restriction enzymes<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Werner_Arber\" title=\"Werner Arber\">Werner Arber<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Daniel_Nathans\" title=\"Daniel Nathans\">Daniel Nathans<\/a> as co-recipients.<\/p><p>He later became a leading figure in the nascent field of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genomics\" title=\"Genomics\">genomics<\/a>, when in 1995 he and a team at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Institute_for_Genomic_Research\" title=\"The Institute for Genomic Research\" class=\"mw-redirect\">The Institute for Genomic Research<\/a> sequenced the first <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bacteria\" title=\"Bacteria\">bacterial<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genome\" title=\"Genome\">genome<\/a>, that of <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Haemophilus_influenzae\" title=\"Haemophilus influenzae\">Haemophilus influenzae<\/a><\/i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> <i>H. influenza<\/i> was the same organism in which Smith had discovered restriction enzymes in the late 1960s. He subsequently played a key role in the sequencing of many of the early genomes at The Institute for Genomic Research, and in the assembly of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Human_genome\" title=\"Human genome\">human genome<\/a> at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Celera_Genomics\" title=\"Celera Genomics\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Celera Genomics<\/a>, which he joined when it was founded in 1998.<\/p><p>More recently, he has directed a team at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/J._Craig_Venter_Institute\" title=\"J. Craig Venter Institute\">J. Craig Venter Institute<\/a> that works towards creating a partially <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Synthetic_biology\" title=\"Synthetic biology\">synthetic<\/a> bacterium, <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mycoplasma_laboratorium\" title=\"Mycoplasma laboratorium\">Mycoplasma laboratorium<\/a><\/i>. In 2003 the same group synthetically assembled the genome of a virus, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Phi_X_174\" title=\"Phi X 174\">Phi X 174<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bacteriophage\" title=\"Bacteriophage\">bacteriophage<\/a>. Currently, Smith is scientific director of privately held <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Synthetic_Genomics\" title=\"Synthetic Genomics\">Synthetic Genomics<\/a>, which was founded in 2005 by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Craig_Venter\" title=\"Craig Venter\">Craig Venter<\/a> to continue this work. Currently, Synthetic Genomics is working to produce <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biofuel\" title=\"Biofuel\">biofuels<\/a> on an industrial-scale using recombinant <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Algae\" title=\"Algae\">algae<\/a> and other microorganisms.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-9\"><span>[<\/span>9<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p><br><\/p><p>This article incorporates CC-BY-2.5 text from the reference<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gitschier_2012_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hamilton_O._Smith#cite_note-Gitschier_2012-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Hamilton O. Smith","place_of_birth":null,"place_of_death":null,"text":"Hamilton O. Smith , Physiology or Medicine, 1978","year":1978.0}